page.title: 10 Landscape of Holbeach Marsh
page.content: The landscape around here is very flat. It's flat because until the Middle Ages there were only little islands with water all around them,and it used to run over all or most of the land. In doing so it would wash away any silt or rocks that may have formed any hills. The water came in rivers that spread out over wide areas and the sea that came in from the Wash. That is why it is not hilly. There is more sky than land around here. There are few trees around but not many. There are lots of potatoes and vegetable fields. The fields are divided by dykes instead of hedges and you can see for a long way. There are also some crops like, wheat, barley and sugar beet. There are lots of smaller fields down the sluice road where there are small holdings.
